<HEADLINE>
<P>
ENVIRONMENT: NOTES ABOUT YOUR SURROUNDINGS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Starr Ranch Field Trip -- The Sea and Sage chapter of the National Audubon 
Society will host a field trip to the Starr Ranch Audubon Sanctuary in Ronald 
W. Caspers Wilderness Park on Saturday. The trip is open to the public, and 
those wishing to participate should meet in the parking lot adjacent to the 
park's entrance booth at 8 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
The trip will include exploring various side roads and canyons in the Bell 
Canyon area of the park. Participants should wear good walking shoes and bring 
binoculars and their lunch. 
</P>
<P>
There is a $2 entrance fee at the park, which is at 33401 Ortega Highway in an 
unincorporated area north of San Juan Capistrano. 
</P>
<P>
Rarities -- It is fall migration time for birds and the best time of year to 
spot lost migrants, which are birds that are rare to the area that have gotten 
lost. According to the Sea and Sage Chapter of the National Audubon Society, 
the number of migrants that have been spotted in the county has been sporadic. 
However, there have been three first-recorded sightings of birds thus far. 
</P>
<P>
An immature blue-footed booby was found Sept. 7 in a weakened condition in a 
Huntington Beach schoolyard. Although taken to a local bird rehabilitation 
center, it died a few days later. 
</P>
<P>
An adult white-rumped sandpiper was spotted by Doug Willick and Loren Hays at 
San Joaquin Marsh in Irvine on Sept. 9 through 13. Also at the marsh, Richard 
Webster spotted a garganeySept. 12. There have been less than 10 sightings of 
this duck, a Eurasian variety of the teal, in California. 
</P>
<P>
Other rarities spotted in September include a white-face ibis at San Joaquin 
Marsh and San Diego Creek; seven greater white-fronted geese and a sage 
thrasher, also at the marsh; a juvenile stilt sandpiper at the Santa Ana River 
in Anaheim; a bay-breasted warbler at Huntington Central Park and a hooded 
warbler at UC Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
Other warblers seen in the county include four Virginia, a Tennessee, several 
palm, blackpoll and black-and-white varieties, and a redstart. 
</P>
</TEXT>
