<HEADLINE>
<P>
PORTRAIT OF A PLANET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Imagine lacy fingers of red coral groping in the silent depths of the Pacific. 
Picture baby seals frolicking on the sun-drenched shores of islands in the 
Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
These are two visions of a planet both beautiful and diverse, unspoiled by 
human activity. Now picture Argentine rivers blackened with oily industrial 
toxins. Imagine Mt. Everest littered with the rusting garbage of countless 
expeditions. These, too, are images of Earth -- and civilization's undeniable 
presence. 
</P>
<P>
 In "One Earth," a collection of color photographs published this month by 
Collins Publishers, 80 photojournalists from around the world have documented 
the gamut of environmental problems, including global warming, pollution, 
deforestation, endangered species and overpopulation. The photographers, many 
of whom contributed to the books "A Day in the Life of America" and "A Day in 
the Life of the Soviet Union," began shooting in August, 1989. Seven months 
later, they had amassed thousands of pictures, producing a dramatic portrait of 
the planet and the state of its fragile natural resources. 
</P>
<P>
"The goal was to present a serious issue in an accessible way, using the power 
of photojournalism," says Kate Kelly, managing editor of the project. "We 
wrestled long and hard with how best to show not only the gravity of the issue 
but also the spirit of hope, the momentum of people worldwide who are trying to 
do something about these problems." 
</P>
<P>
All photographs from "One Earth," 1990 by Collins Publishers. Reprinted by 
permission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, In Brazil, developers have built roads and burned acres of rain 
forest, above. H. W. Silvester/ Rapho/ Black Star; Photo, COLOR, At a tin mine 
in Rondonia, Brazil, below, the tropical Amazon landscape is as barren as a 
desert. J. Kyle Keener/ Philadelphia Inquirer/ Matrix; Photo, COLOR, In 
Washington state, the timber industry has clear-cut miles of forest, right. 
Daniel Dancer; Photo, COLOR, On the Quinalt Indian Reservation on Washington's 
Olympic Peninsula, above, two Quinalts plant saplings. Jim Richardson 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA111190-0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 306783 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 11, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
